literally mike gross 2022-10-15 3:51 PM
When the sugar cane arrives at the mill, that‚Äôs where the real fun begins. First, the stalks are washed, cut into shreds, and pressed using big rollers. The juice is separated from the plant material, then the liquid is boiled until it crystallizes. Finally, the crystals are separated from the liquid using a centrifuge, yielding raw sugar. Hold on, though: this isn‚Äôt the same ‚Äúraw sugar‚Äù you can buy at the grocery store. At this point, it still has lots of impurities, so it‚Äôs sent to a cane sugar refinery to be filtered. From here, sugar goes through various treatments depending on what type of sugar it will ultimately become. Fun fact: all sugar is harvested the same; it‚Äôs not until it gets to the mill that it turns into different types of sugar, such as granulated sugar and brown sugar. According to the American Sugar Refining Group, a sugar cane stalk is 72% water, 12% sugar, 13% fiber and 3% molasses. White granulated sugar is made by removing all of the molasses. Brown sugar retains some of the molasses, which gives it its darker color. Fun fact: sugar cane fiber can be turned into disposable plates, bowls and takeout containers. Read more about it here.
-tasteofhome.com
